sec.p:
Raw materials (R) are modeled as a stock that decreases through consumption in production and increases through procurement. The dynamics are governed by:
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d R(t)}{d t}=\lambda_{r}(t)-\mu_{r}(t) R(t) \tag{1}
\end{equation*}
where $\lambda_{r}(t)$ represents the procurement rate of raw materials, $\mu_{r}(t)$ denotes the rate at which raw materials are consumed and transferred to WIP. This formulation extends traditional economic order quantity models [7] by incorporating time-varying rates.

Work-in-Progress (W) represents items undergoing transformation but not yet completed. Its dynamics are modeled by:
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d W(t)}{d t}=\mu_{r}(t) R(t)-\mu_{w}(t) W(t) \tag{2}
\end{equation*}
where $\mu_{r}(t) R(t)$ is the rate at which raw materials are converted into WIP, $\mu_{w}(t) W(t)$ represents the rate at which WIP is processed into finished goods. This approach aligns with recent work on production-inventory systems [9].

Finished Goods (F) represent completed products ready for distribution. Their dynamics follow:
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d F(t)}{d t}=\mu_{w}(t) W(t)-\lambda_{f}(t) F(t) \tag{3}
\end{equation*}
where $\mu_{w}(t) W(t)$ is the rate at which WIP is converted into finished goods, $\lambda_{f}(t)$ represents the rate at which finished goods are sold or dispatched. This formulation extends traditional inventory models [13] by incorporating time-dependent demand patterns.

Holding cost: The cost of storing inventory over time is defined as:
\begin{equation*}
C_{u}=\int_{0}^{T}\left(C_{R} R(t)+C_{W} W(t)+C_{F} F(t)\right) d t \tag{4}
\end{equation*}
where $C_{R}, C_{W}$, and $C_{F}$ represent the holding costs per unit of raw materials, WIP, and finished goods, respectively.

Procurement Cost: The expense of acquiring raw materials is given by:
\begin{equation*}
C_{p}=\int_{0}^{T} K_{R} \lambda_{r}(t) d t \tag{5}
\end{equation*}
where $K_{R}$ represents the procurement cost per unit of raw materials

Production Cost: The expenses incurred during manufacturing are defined as:
\begin{equation*}
C_{s}=\int_{0}^{T}\left(K_{W} \mu_{w}(t) W(t)\right) d t \tag{6}
\end{equation*}
where $K_{W}$ is the production cost per unit of WIP.

The following differential equations govern the system dynamics:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{gathered}
\frac{d R(t)}{d t}=\lambda_{r}(t)-\mu_{r}(t) R(t) \tag{7}\\
\frac{d W(t)}{d t}=\mu_{r}(t) R(t)-\mu_{w}(t) W(t) \tag{8}\\
\frac{d F(t)}{d t}=\mu_{w}(t) W(t)-\lambda_{f}(t) F(t)
\end{gathered} \tag{9}
\end{equation*}

Non-Negativity Constraints All variables must be non-negative:
\begin{equation*}
R(t), W(t), F(t), \lambda_{r}(t), \mu_{r}(t), \mu_{w}(t), \lambda_{f}(t) \geq 0 \tag{10}
\end{equation*}

Objective Function The goal is to minimize total cost:
\begin{equation*}
C_{t o t a l}=H_{t o t a l}+P_{1}+P_{2} \tag{11}
\end{equation*}
where $H_{\text {total }}$ is total holding cost, $P_{1}$ is procurement cost, and $P_{2}$ is production cost.

Expression for Total Cost The total cost is expressed as:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
C_{\text {total }}= & \int_{0}^{T}\left(h_{R} \cdot R(t)+h_{W} \cdot W(t)+h_{F} \cdot F(t)\right. \\
& \left.+c_{R} \cdot \lambda_{r}(t)+c_{P} \cdot \mu_{w}(t) \cdot W(t)\right) d t
\end{aligned} \tag{12}
\end{equation*}

Hamiltonian Construction: The Hamiltonian incorporates the total cost and state dynamics:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
H= & h_{R} \cdot R(t)+h_{W} \cdot W(t)+h_{F} \cdot F(t)+c_{R} \cdot \lambda_{r}(t) \\
& +c_{P} \cdot \mu_{w}(t) \cdot W(t)+\psi_{R}(t) \cdot\left(\lambda_{r}(t)-\mu_{R} \cdot R(t)\right) \\
& +\psi_{W}(t) \cdot\left(\mu_{R} \cdot R(t)-\mu_{W} \cdot W(t)\right) \\
& +\psi_{F}(t) \cdot\left(\mu_{W} \cdot W(t)-\lambda_{F} \cdot F(t)\right)
\end{aligned} \tag{13}
\end{equation*}

Optimality Conditions: In the context of this inventory management problem, the Hamiltonian function H represents the total instantaneous cost of the system, combining both the direct costs (such as inventory holding and procurement) and the impact of the system's dynamics through the co-state variables. It is a central component of Pontryagin's Maximum Principle used to derive the optimal control policy. This function encapsulates the system's objectives and constraints, and it is used to derive the necessary conditions for optimality, including the co-state equations and optimal control laws. The optimal control $\lambda_{r}^{*}(t), \mu_{r}^{*}(t), \mu_{w}^{*}(t), \lambda_{f}^{*}(t)$ minimizes the Hamiltonian:
\begin{equation*}
u^{*}(t)=\arg \min _{u(t)} H(x(t), u(t), \psi(t), t) \tag{14}
\end{equation*}

Co-state Equations The co-state variables evolve according to:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
\frac{d \psi_{R}(t)}{d t} & =-\frac{\partial H}{\partial R(t)} \tag{15}\\
\frac{d \psi_{W}(t)}{d t} & =-\frac{\partial H}{\partial W(t)} \tag{16}\\
\frac{d \psi_{F}(t)}{d t} & =-\frac{\partial H}{\partial F(t)}
\end{aligned} \tag{17}
\end{equation*}

Boundary Conditions The final boundary conditions for co-state variables are:
\begin{equation*}
\psi_{R}(T)=0, \psi_{W}(T)=0, \psi_{F}(T)=0 \tag{18}
\end{equation*}

The system was simulated over a total time horizon of $T=10$ units, divided into 100 equally spaced time points. The initial conditions were defined as:
\begin{equation*}
R(0)=100, \quad W(0)=0, \quad F(0)=0.
\end{equation*}

Periodic Inventory Replenishment Function We implemented a periodic replenishment function:
\begin{equation*}
\operatorname{Replenishment}(t)= \begin{cases}\text { rate }, & \text { if }(t \bmod \text { period })=0 \\ 0, & \text { otherwise }\end{cases} \tag{19}
\end{equation*}

We modeled the three-compartment inventory system with periodic raw material replenishment (pulses) following the approach in [17]:
\begin{equation*}
\lambda_{r}(t)= \begin{cases}\lambda_{r}, & \text { if }(t \text { mod cycle time })<\text { pulse duration } \\ 0, & \text { otherwise }\end{cases}
\end{equation*}
